  <div class=3D"insights">
    <h3>Key Observations</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>First-class women had the highest survival rate (~96%) =E2=80=94 =
the safest group aboard</li>
      <li>Third-class men had the lowest survival rate (~14%) =E2=80=94 the=
 most at-risk group</li>
      <li>Even 3rd-class women (~55%) survived at a higher rate than 1st-cl=
ass men (~37%), confirming gender dominated class as a survival factor</li>
      <li>The class gap among men is stark: 1st-class men survived at 2.6=
=C3=97 the rate of 3rd-class men</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- CONCLUSIONS -->
<div class=3D"section">
  <h2>8 =C2=B7 Summary &amp; Conclusions</h2>
  <p>A consolidated view of the key findings and recommended next steps for=
 modelling.</p>
  <div class=3D"insights" style=3D"background:linear-gradient(135deg,#EFF6F=
F,#FEF9C3)">
    <h3>Top Factors Influencing Survival</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Gender</strong> is the single most powerful predictor =E2=
=80=94 women survived at 3.7=C3=97 the rate of men</li>
      <li><strong>Passenger class</strong> directly proxies socioeconomic s=
tatus and lifeboat access</li>
      <li><strong>Fare</strong> is a continuous proxy for class and cabin l=
ocation =E2=80=94 higher fare =E2=86=92 closer to lifeboats</li>
      <li><strong>Age</strong> mattered primarily at the extremes: children=
 were prioritised, seniors were disadvantaged</li>
      <li><strong>Family size</strong> of 1=E2=80=933 was optimal; solo and=
 large-group passengers fared worse</li>
      <li><strong>Port of embarkation</strong> is a proxy for class composi=
tion, not a direct survival factor</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
  <div class=3D"insights" style=3D"margin-top:16px;background:linear-gradie=
nt(135deg,#F0FDF4,#ECFDF5)">
    <h3>Recommended Next Steps</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Impute missing Age values using median by Sex =C3=97 Pclass sub-g=
roup</li>
      <li>Engineer <em>FamilySize</em> =3D SibSp + Parch and <em>IsAlone</e=
m> binary flag</li>
      <li>Apply log-transform to Fare before modelling to reduce skew</li>
      <li>Build a baseline Logistic Regression, then compare with Random Fo=
rest and Gradient Boosting</li>
      <li>Use SHAP values post-modelling to confirm feature importances qua=
ntitatively</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</div>

